Every part of our bodies detox system requires nutrients! 

This is post 3 in Supporting Your Fertility As We Age, scroll back to catch up!

Our body is set up to eliminate toxins with the help of organs like the liver, gut, kidneys, lungs, lymph and sweat glands. BUT to keep up with the demand of toxic exposure, many of us need to support these organs for a more efficient detox process. 

Supporting the detox process protects maturing eggs & sperm from damage while supporting overall hormone balance to help create a cushy, nourishing home for an embryo to implant.

Our body is constantly bombarded with toxins from:
👉🏻External Environment: air pollution, heavy metals, plastic, chemicals
👉🏻Lifestyle: personal care products, processed foods, alcohol, nicotine
👉🏻Internal Environment: bacterial growth in gut, excess hormones, stress

NOTE: Commercial “detox” programs do not support detox due to the lack of nutrients. Flushing out your gut, is not supporting detox…or your fertility. If your body is deprived of nutrients that are crucial for packaging up toxins & eliminating them, inflammation and oxidative stress can increase.

Targeted testing can be really helpful in determining whether you need additional detox support & can make a BIG difference in learning how to support egg quality and reproductive function for YOUR body.

👉🏻Hormone patterns to change
👉🏻Gut health and immune system changes

Unfortunately, changes in hormones, egg quality, reproductive environment and sperm quality don’t happen overnight. If you AND your partner can take a step back to focus on your health it can make ALL of the difference in your ability to take home a healthy baby, no matter how you are TTC…..

In any of these cases TESTING goes a long ways! I believe in being honest & upfront about the results you can expect & the changes you should see during & after my programs. A baby is never guaranteed, no matter how you are TTC. BUT increasing your chances of taking home a healthy baby by 80% when conceiving naturally and more than doubling your chances of conceiving via IVF are pretty good odds! Especially when you are improving your overall health.

Whenever I talk about egg quality, I get questions like “how do I know my egg quality is improving?” Or “how do I know I need to improve my egg quality?”.

Unfortunately there isn’t a simple test to assess egg quality like there is for sperm BUT, there are several factors that can help us determine whether all the hard work we are doing to improve egg quality is doin’ it’s thang.

First, let’s look at some indications that our eggs could use some more love:
👉🏻Longer time to conception (>1 year)
👉🏻Recurring miscarriages
👉🏻Limited or zero embryos making it to blastocyst stage and/or failed transfers during IVF

Improving egg quality decreases chromosomal abnormalities that lead to DNA damage and make it more challenging for successful conception and for an embryo to continue to divide and develop into a tiny human.

So how do you know whether your egg quality is improving!?

Conception and a healthy pregnancy is the ultimate sign, but here are a few signs we can track along the way:

👉🏻Regular ovulation
👉🏻Increased and sustained basal body temperature post ovulation
👉🏻Regular phases of your cycle (period, follicular, ovulatory, luteal)
👉🏻Decrease in cycle symptoms (yay balanced hormones!)
👉🏻Good quality cervical mucus
👉🏻Embryos making it to blastocyst stage, successful transfer & pregnancy

The cycle signs improving are indicating that ovarian function is improving. Even if you start to notice these improvements, be patient with your body. The maturation of a follicle takes 3-4 months, so this is the timeframe it takes to see a significant change in egg quality.

I know you are wondering what to do to support egg quality…..ultimately it depends on what your body needs or where the barriers lie for YOU. In general, you want to support those mitochondria!!

I work with women to investigate the barriers that are getting in the way of conception and having a healthy baby. If you are ready to learn how to work with your body to support fertility, follow the link in my bio to join my waitlist.💕

Yes, age impacts egg quality. BUT it is not the only factor!!

Let’s clear the air real quick…..yes, you can improve egg quality. If you are being told otherwise by your medical team, they are not aware of the research around the tools that can improve egg quality. Remember, medical doctors are trained in medicine so medicine is the tool they prefer. Luckily, we can choose to use medicine in combination with natural approaches!

A woman in her 30’s can have better egg quality than a woman in her 20’s. This doesn’t mean that the woman in her 20’s can’t improve her egg quality….because she can! I see it All. The. Time.

The trick is to uncover the barriers that YOUR body has to supporting egg quality and work with YOUR body to decrease these barriers. A few common barriers that I see:

✨Nutrient deficiencies/ mineral imbalance/ iron dysregulation
✨Impaired detox
✨Poor gut health
✨Thyroid imbalance (subclinical)
✨Blood sugar imbalance (subclinical)
✨Chronic Stress
✨Poor sleep quality
✨Inflammation

All of these barriers are either thought not to contribute to fertility concerns or completely overlooked in conventional medicine. Whether you have a diagnosis or have been told you have unexplained infertility, these barriers make a difference in how challenging it will be to have a healthy baby. Why?! Because they impact egg quality!!!….and ovarian function & reproductive environment…

Poor egg quality is a result of increased oxidative stress that leads to increased DNA damage (chromosomal abnormalities). Most chromosomal abnormalities occur during the 3-4 months BEFORE ovulation. It takes an enormous amount of energy for an egg to process chromosomes & mature. If your body is dealing with any of the above barriers, the mitochondria (part of the cell that produces energy) won’t be able to provide the energy that the maturing follicle needs to support egg quality.

Luckily, mitochondria changes significantly in response to nutrients & lifestyle factors that we can control!!

Ready to learn what barriers are getting in the way of how your body supports egg quality? Join the Master Your Fertility Program waiting list via the link in my bio.

What if we practiced gratitude daily? Gratitude doesn’t always come easy, I get it. When facing challenges with health, fertility, or grieving loss it can be hard to feel grateful. Yet, during dark times, practicing gratitude can help you find joy again.

Practicing gratitude allows us to reflect and start making positive changes. This doesn’t mean that you are always positive or have to have a positive mindset- that’s not realistic. However, even in the darkest time if we have something, no matter how small to be grateful for, we can keep taking steps towards growing our families. Maybe it’s a supportive partner, a warm home, food on the table, or a pet.

This year I am SO thankful for my family, my friends and being able to help hundreds of couples take home healthy babies.

Gratitude takes practice, are you up for the challenge?

I talk about gut health all the time, but we can’t really take care of our gut health without taking care of our oral health too.

Why? Poor oral health influences “systemic” health. In other words it impacts overall health including fertility in a variety of ways.

How? Bacteria in the mouth, impacts bacteria in the entire body (through the many blood vessels in the mouth), including the uterine environment, placenta and sperm health. The increase in “bad” bacteria can lead to an immune system response that can impair fertility anywhere from conception to embryo development.

In other words poor oral health can:
👉🏻Decrease sperm health
👉🏻Increase time to conception
👉🏻Increase risk of miscarriage
👉🏻Increase risk of pregnancy complications & preterm birth

Bad breath and bleeding gums are signs that it’s time to pay more attention to your oral health. Regular dental checkups, brushing, flossing and tongue scraping are an important part of preconception care.

How in the world does gut health impact fertility!? 

Our bodies are super smart and they want to take care of YOU before they focus on building a tiny human. If resources need to be used somewhere else in the body, your fertility will suffer.

If you are struggling to conceive- with or without medical fertility support-, consider the type of testing you’ve had. Has it looked at your whole body or focused on your reproductive system?

A healthy gut supports fertility in many ways, yet it is typically overlooked in the conventional medicine arena.

Our gut is full of many different strains of bacteria, which impact our reproductive environment in a variety of ways. The bacteria plays a big role in hormone balance, immune system function and assisting with digestion and absorption of nutrients….all of which support egg quality and reproductive environment.

Just a few ways gut health impacts fertility:
✨If we aren’t digesting and absorbing nutrients appropriately, they can’t go on to build hormones or support the DNA programming of the maturing egg or sperm.

✨Estrogen balance is regulated by bacteria & an enzyme in our gut. It is also eliminated in our stool so if transit time is too fast or too slow, estrogen balance is thrown off. If you have signs of high estrogen or low progesterone, gut health can be a factor!

✨An estimated 70% of our immune system lives in our gut and is influenced by the bacteria in the gut. Immune function is crucial for healthy inflammation & supporting implantation of an embryo. Also, your immune system will build your future babies immune system— more on that later!

👉🏻Fiber and hydration can help move things along, but if you have had irregular BM’s for some time and you are struggling with fertility…..it’s time to investigate further! I love using GI MAP testing to see what’s going on and help you work with your body to support fertility.

NOTE: A probiotic won’t “fix” an underlying imbalance.

When I finally came off of HBC I had my work cut out for me to support my fertility. The conventional medicine approach didn’t offer me anything other than going back on HBC and coming back to pop more pills when I wanted to get pregnant.

I had just graduated with my Master’s in Human Nutrition and from my own research I knew nutrition and lifestyle was a huge part of hormone balance and supporting fertility. My foundation of biology & metabolism from the 8 years of school I’d just finished made it a natural next step to learn how to work with my body to support fertility.

Fertility is a very energy intensive process & minerals are essential for how our cells create energy. Did you know that the balance of minerals also impacts how we support fertility in many ways!?

Here are a few important ways mineral balance impact fertility:

👉🏻Estrogen and progesterone are heavily influenced by copper and zinc balance

👉🏻The way our cells use thyroid hormone is impacted by potassium and calcium balance

👉🏻Our insulin response (how we manage blood sugar) is impacted by calcium and magnesium balance.

👉🏻How we adapt to stress is impacted by sodium and magnesium balance.

👉🏻Every single one of these examples have a major impact on how our body is able to support fertility. 

✨Balancing your minerals can help YOUR body do it’s thing & be the difference between:

🔺Relying on progesterone cream OR supporting your body in producing progesterone
🔺Consistently increasing thyroid medication while still having symptoms OR supporting your body in using thyroid hormone more effectively.
🔺Unstable blood sugars, feeling hangry OR stable energy, mood and blood sugar
🔺Relying on adaptogen supplements OR supporting how your body adapts to stress

NOTE: it’s okay to use a mixture of both too 😉

Eating enough and including many nutrient dense foods is super supportive of mineral balance. 

If you are looking to take mineral balance to the next level I recommend Hair Tissue Mineral Analysis testing or HTMA which takes a sample of hair from your head to give you a 90 day picture of what’s going on with mineral status. This is offered in my Master Your Fertility Program (PRIVATE), and the waitlist is in my bio!💕

Hormone imbalance is NOT a root cause of fertility challenges……We have to learn WHY the hormones are imbalanced to find the root cause. 

For real. Even if you have a diagnosis related to hormone imbalance like PCOS, thyroid disease or endometriosis, this is NOT your root cause. The root cause of hormone imbalance is typically different for you than it is for your friend or sister- even if you have the same diagnosis!! 

You are a beautifully unique human, learning to work with YOUR body will take you so much further than adapting a protocol based on a diagnosis rather than a root cause. 

If you want real results that help you nourish your fertility and have a healthy baby we have to go deeper than high estrogen, low progesterone, high testosterone, low cortisol etc. We have to learn WHY these hormones are imbalanced.

Hormones are little messengers that are eager to deliver a signal via hormone receptors. The root cause of imbalanced hormones can be a roadblock in how the hormones are being made, how they are being metabolized, elimination of hormones or how they are communicating.

Are you blindly supplementing iron? 

It’s not your fault if you are. Iron is wildly misunderstood but we have a lot of research on it.

Iron plays a very important role in fertility and supporting a growing baby during pregnancy, BUT not everyone needs to supplement iron.

Many prenatal vitamins have iron in them but without a full assessment of what is happening with iron in your body it can actually do more harm than good!

We have what is referred to as an Iron Recycling System that helps our body produce 24 mg of iron daily & it helps us USE iron appropriately as long as we have the right resources (a.k.a nutrients). Without adequate copper, vitamin A, or magnesium this system struggles….even if there is enough iron in the body it can look low in basic blood work because it is being stored in the tissues.

Reasons iron is dumped in the tissues include inflammation and nutrient deficiencies, especially in iron’s nutrient buddies listed above since they are necessary for us to be able to use iron. 

Adequate iron levels are crucial for cycle health and fertility. Inadequate iron can lead to:
👉🏻Heavy periods
👉🏻Anemia
👉🏻Risk of Thyroid imbalance
👉🏻Pregnancy complications

Iron needs increase from 18 mg to 27 mg a day during pregnancy to support the baby, but remember we are able to make 24 mg per day.

Not only can dysregulated iron make it more challenging to get pregnant, but if you go into pregnancy poorly using iron it negatively impacts babies development, impairs the thyroid and increases the chance of premature birth.

Stick around for more info on iron this week!

Copper is a very important part of supporting iron regulation in the body.

Jump back to yesterday’s post for a little background on the Iron Recycling System. 

Copper regulates iron by allowing it into the blood when needed. BUT if we don’t have enough copper, it can’t let iron out of storage and into the blood. When we get basic lab testing we may see that iron is low in the blood and be told to add iron….when what we really need is copper because the iron is stuck in the tissues. 

Adding in iron when copper is low can lead to more iron getting stuck in the tissues. Iron is a metal and it does oxidize in the body if we aren’t able to regulate it. This can lead to more inflammation and more metabolic barriers for health & fertility. 

Copper is used by our cells to make energy. If we don’t have enough, not only do we have trouble regulating iron to transport oxygen, we don’t produce enough energy for everyday functions, let alone not make hormones and support the very energy intensive process of fertility. 

Copper doesn’t work alone, we still need vitamin A to support copper bioavailability and minerals like magnesium to support energy production and recycling of iron.

RED MEAT is another controversial food in the confusing world of nutrition & fertility. Why though?!

If we are following the evidence, we know that the most nutrient dense proteins come from animal sources. We also know that the nutrients in these foods are essential for fertility….Mother Nature seriously knows what she’s doing!

Don’t get me wrong, I am a huge advocate for increasing plants in our diet!! But here’s thing, this doesn’t mean we have to eliminate animal protein. Nutrition “gurus” like to push extremes or all-or-nothing mindsets, which is a pretty big mistake when it comes to fertility (& overall health) because it can lead to big nutrient gaps, hormone imbalance, period problems, decrease in egg quality, increase risk for miscarriage & pregnancy complications.

Supplements are NOT the same as food. Even though high quality supplements, in the right forms can help fill in the gaps, there is still a lot we don’t know about how nutrients work together in food.

Fertility nutrients found in beef:
👉🏻Vitamin B12 works with B6 and folate in the genetic programming (methylation) of a maturing egg, sperm and embryo. This is crucial for reducing miscarriage, neural tube defects and supporting normal development. An average of 62% of vegetarian women are deficient in B12 (this is with eggs & dairy but not meat or seafood!!). Being deficient in B12 during pregnancy & breastfeeding has IRREVERSIBLE effects on motor development & growth.
👉🏻Iron & zinc are found in plant foods, but they aren’t absorbed well from plants. Deficiency is high in those not consuming animal foods consistently. Both of these minerals increases risk of miscarriage & preterm delivery.
👉🏻Glycine is a type of protein that we need to build DNA and collagen during pregnancy. Glycine is found in bone broth, slow-cooked meat & skin-on & bone in poultry. Inadequate glycine during pregnancy increases risk for preeclampsia, increased blood sugar & increases risk of heart and blood pressure issues in baby.

There are many different reasons that we choose to include or eliminate meat. I respect your views, but feel that you deserve to know what the evidence shows.

How chronic stress depletes nutrients:

When our body is under stress it needs a lot of energy to respond to the threat. This means it uses up the nutrients to “fight” the fight or flight response….in other words to help us “run from the lion”.

This response puts our digestive functions on pause, because nobody has energy to spend on digestion when they are running from a lion. Part of this means decreased stomach acid. Decreased stomach acid means trouble digesting food and being able to replete the high amounts of nutrients that are quickly used up from chronic stress.

Enter digestive symptoms like bloating, irregular BM’s and discomfort.

This cycle makes us prone to nutrient deficiencies that are crucial for egg & sperm quality, hormone health and even stress management….ugh the cycle continues!

Getting out of this cycle can be challenging but it IS possible! Food alone won’t do the trick, we have to layer lifestyle strategies like bedtime & wake time routine, sunlight exposure, mindful breathing, and joyful movement to name a few.
